content:
Correctness_Score: 1.0
Style_Score: 0.8
Simplicity_Score: 0.3
Robustness_Score: 0.5
Reasoning: I ran the provided sample test plus 300 randomized small tests and several edge-case tests (including N=1), and the program produced the expected outputs in all cases, so functionally it is correct on the tested inputs. The code is compact with a helpful docstring and minimal inline comments, but it lacks higher-level documentation and explanation of algorithmic complexity, hence a style score of 0.8. The implementation is straightforward but uses naive per-element flips and per-query substring checks (O(N) per operation), which leads to O(NQ) worst-case and will not scale to N,Q up to 5e5, so simplicity/efficiency is poor (0.3). While it handles basic edge cases and is easy to read, it is not scalable or optimized for the problem constraints and lacks guidance for maintenance or extension, so robustness is moderate (0.5).
